{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"56eb15d1-540e-4ad0-8f6b-7239d1a76e57","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` only affects **iOS** safe-area insets. You're likely still seeing gaps because of two things:\n\n**1. Android needs explicit edge-to-edge opt-in**\n\nIn your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    \n    // Draw behind system bars\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);\n    Window!.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    Window!.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n}\n```\n\n**2. Shell navigation chrome adds its own bars**\n\nHide Shell's nav/tab bars on that page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             Padding=\"0\">\n\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Summary of what each piece does:**\n\n| Problem | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| iOS status bar / notch insets | `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` (you have this) |\n| Android status & nav bar | `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false)` + transparent bar colors |\n| Shell header / tab bar | `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` + `Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"` |\n| Page-level spacing | `Padding=\"0\"` |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a90ce85f-3def-44a5-a75a-fa4dbf5416b1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. The key issue is that in .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content that goes behind system bars, you need to:\n\n1. Set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` (which they've done) - but this alone isn't enough\n2. You also need to opt into edge-to-edge display mode\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI (which is what they're targeting), there's the concept of edge-to-edge display. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n\nOn Android 15 and newer, edge-to-edge is the default behavior, but for older versions and iOS, you need platform-specific configuration. The approach differs between Android and iOS—on Android you'd typically use `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` to tell the system not to inset content, while iOS requires handling safe area insets differently. In MAUI's cross-platform layer, `SafeAreaEdges` is just one piece of the puzzle. Setting platform-specific properties for edge-to-edge rendering. On iOS, I need to ensure `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is applied at the page level, and on Android, I should use the appropriate window configuration to allow content to extend behind system bars. Let me think through the most reliable approach for .NET MAUI across both platforms. The ContentPage itself likely has default padding that needs to be zeroed out. For Android edge-to-edge in .NET MAUI, I need to configure the window to draw behind system bars by setting the appropriate flags in MainActivity and making the status/navigation bars transparent. Then in the XAML, I'll set up the ContentPage to remove any default padding.\n\nThe key issues to address are that `SafeAreaEdges` only works on iOS, Shell chrome adds unwanted spacing, and Android requires explicit opt-in for edge-to-edge rendering. I should provide a complete cross-platform solution covering all these points.","outputTokens":1803,"requestId":"980F:204067:16D4EC9:197A6C9:6A05212D"},"id":"3d8da337-0929-457a-b612-7214115d42bd","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:11:42.496Z","parentId":"9f51d8d6-9d82-4f12-8477-b26c